Keep in mind that the generic method signature

```ts
{
  applyPreMiddleware<T extends SomeType = SomeType>(it: T, opts: B): Promise<T | undefined>
}
```

is mostly just syntactic sugar for the following property declaration:

```ts
{
  applyPreMiddleware: <T extends SomeType = SomeType>(it: T, opts: B) => Promise<T | undefined>
}
```

So I think you want this:

```ts
type ApplyMiddleware<Constraint> = 
  <T extends Constraint = Constraint>(it: T, opts: B) => Promise<T | undefined>

interface X {
  applyPreMiddleware: ApplyMiddleware<SomeType>;
  applyPostMiddleware: ApplyMiddleware<SomeTypePostProcessing>;
}
```

```ts

interface X {
  applyPreMiddleware: ApplyMiddleware<SomeType>;
  applyPostMiddleware: ApplyMiddleware<SomeTypePostProcessing>;
}
```

Thanks @DanielRosenwasser.

If I'm understanding correctly, though, I don't think your suggestion is exactly what I'm asking for. In particular, I want to allow the user of the `X` to set the parameter at each call site of one of the `applyMiddleware` methods (e.g., so they get a more specific Promise out); in your version, though, the value for the parameters seems to be set once and forever in the definition of `X`.

