comments.body:
You have two options:

Either annotate the value, not the variable
```ts
const fn = <T>(p: T): [T, T] => {
    // Work: tmp and tmp2 are of type T. Via implicit inference.
    const tmp = p
    const tmp2 = identity(p)
    const tmp3 = identity<T>('string') // error

    return [tmp, tmp2]
}
```
Or to create a type alias:
```ts
const fn2: <T>(p: T) => [T, T] = p => {
    type T = typeof p

    const tmp: T = p
    const tmp2 = identity<T>(p)
    const tmp3 = identity<T>('string') // error

    return [tmp, tmp2]
}
```

Basically, variable declaration annotations don't share their scope with a possible literal implementation.

