TypeScript won't look at the `tsconfig.json` for imported modules. So it won't know that in `git-submodule` you had a `tsconfig.json` that included the types.
If you need to expose types from a package, you should reference them from its `index` in some way, such as with `/// <reference path="./types/custom.d.ts" />.`
In this case, you could also not bother with putting types in a separate file and just do:
```ts
declare global {
    interface Date {
        format(): number;
    }
}
```

@andy-ms 
It works great.

Furthermore, defined types of root project(e.g: `/// <reference path="./root-project.d.ts" />`) will expose to sub-project which can use those types in `root-project.d.ts` file even if sub-project does not define those types. And compiling code will not throw type error, it's unreasonable.

