```ts
interface BaseType {
    "foo":string;
    "bar":number;
}
type WrappedType = {
    [P in keyof BaseType]: { contents: BaseType[P] }; 
}
function openPresent<P extends keyof BaseType>(present: WrappedType, key: P) {
    var v = present[key].contents;
    // next line is an error because the type of v
    // is inferred as string | number instead of BaseType[P]
    var v: BaseType[P]; 
} 
```

I'm guessing this is a design limitation?  Anyway this workaround might help:
```ts
function addToMappedType<P extends keyof BaseType>(mapped:MappedType, key:P, value:BaseType[P]) {
    let array = mapped[key] as BaseType[P][]; // explicit cast
    array.push(value); // no error now
}
```

Try this

```ts
interface BaseType {
    "foo":string;
    "bar":number;
}

type Arrayify<T> = {
    [P in keyof T]: T[P][]
}

function addToMappedType<T extends BaseType, P extends keyof T>(mapped: Arrayify<T>, key: P, value: T[P]) {
    let array = mapped[key];
    array.push(value);
}
```

here I've

1. Rewritten `MappedType` as a homomorphic mapped type called `Arrayify`.
2. Created a new type for `T` that is constrained to `BaseType`.
3. Used the keys of `T` as the constraint of `P` so that you can re-index into `T` correctly.
     * You can also index into `Arrayify<T>` with `P` because it's a homomorphic mapped type so the keys are well-known. That's where things start to come together.

