comments.body:
Classes have two interfaces, the instance interface and the static interface of the constructor function.  You are trying to assign something that is a class to something that is a simple object interface.  The static interface can be referenced as `typeof AShim` and `new AShim()` would produce something that is assignable to `A`.

To describe an interface that `AShim` could be assigned to, it would look like this:

``` typescript
interface AConstructor {
    new (): A;
    prototype: A;
}

var A: AConstructor = AShim;
```

Why it works for other cases like this:

``` ts

interface Blob {
    size: number;
    type: string;
    msClose(): void;
    msDetachStream(): any;
    slice(start?: number, end?: number, contentType?: string): Blob;
}

declare var Blob: {
    prototype: Blob;
    new (blobParts?: any[], options?: BlobPropertyBag): Blob;
}

class BlobShim implements Blob {
    constructor(blobParts?: any[], options?: BlobPropertyBag) { }
    msDetachStream(): any {}
    slice(start?: number, end?: number, contentType?: string): Blob {
        return null;
    }
    msClose(): void {}
    type: string;
    size: number;
}

// OK
var Blob: {
    prototype: Blob;
    new(blobParts?: any[], options?: BlobPropertyBag): Blob;
} = BlobShim;
```

