**TypeScript Version:** 

1.8.10

**Code**

``` ts
class Item1Stuff {}
interface Item1 {
    stuff: Item1Stuff;
}

class Item2Stuff {}
interface Item2 {
    stuff: Item2Stuff;
}

type Item = Item1 | Item2;

function handler(item: Item) {
    return item.stuff;
}
```

**Expected behavior:**
The inferred return type of the `handler` function should be `Item1Stuff | Item2Stuff` no matter how they're implemented since they are completely unrelated classes.

**Actual behavior:** 
The return type is inferred to be `Item1Stuff`. This only changes if `Item1Stuff` implements any property/method (doesn't need to be public) that does not exist in `Item2Stuff` or only exists with another signature.

Note that this only works this way around -- if `Item2Stuff` implements something not contained in `Item1Stuff` it doesn't change anything.

comments.body:
This seems like wrong behavior regardless of the type system. At the very least it's confusing to see the wrong return type. In @Loilo's example, given the call `handler(myItem2)`, TS will report that it has returned an instance of `Item1Stuff`, which is incorrect; only the instance members are the same.

Another example:

``` ts
function doStuff(input: Float32ArrayConstructor|Float64ArrayConstructor) {
    return new input(2);
} // inferred output type is "Float32Array"
doStuff(Float64Array) // claims this is a Float32Array
```

We can override the inferred return type with the same union type as the params, but then the result of `doStuff` remains a union type as well.

