  testNumber(foo['s']);  // fail
  testNumber(foo['asd']);  // pass
}
```

`foo.asd` in this case fails because `asd` is not a valid property of `IFoo`. But `foo['asd']` is assumed to be of type `any`.

I read somewhere that this behavior is intentional to offer some kind of backdoor. I am pretty sure I do not need that backdoor in my project, but I need `foo['asd']` to fail. So it would be great if this behavior could be optionally turned on.

I guess the `--noImplicitAny` option would have some effect, but unfortunately turning it on would require major changes in the rest of my codebase, so that is not an option.

comments.body:
JavaScript allows to index into any object. TypeScript compiler can not statically know type checked all these, e.g. `var name = getName(); x[name];`. so it gives it the type `any`.

Obviously this is not type-safe, for this you have index signatures on types, e.g.

``` ts
interface IFoo {
  n: number;
  s: string;
  [x:string] : number | string;
}

testNumber(foo['asd']);  // now fails
```

`--noImplicitAny` enforces that you can not access into anything without either 1. using known property names (e.g. `foo["n"]` above), or 2. having an index signature on the type as outlined above.

However when the index type is a number you loose some more typing. 

The compiler seems to be lost when doing:
```
interface IFoo {
        [x: number]: number | string;
}
var t = foo['a']; // t = any
```

The equivalent, but using string as index key, works as expected even with "wrong" accessor type:
```
interface IFoo {
        [x: string]: number | string;
}
var t = foo[0]; // t = number | string;
``` 

This is perhaps a silly example but becomes odd when using enums as keys.
And in 2.1.5 you can't use enums as accessors yet so you have to use key:number.  

@mhegazy any recommendations of usage here? (e.g. not getting back type:any when using key:number)


Using 2.1.5 in examples

``` ts
interface ITest{test?:string}; let test:ITest={}
```

