In general, these questions are better fit for StackOverflow, but since you're already here it's not a problem. :smile: 

This is an annoying subtlety. Basically type assertions check assignability in both directions. `this._type` can't be assigned to `ClassOf<T>`, because `T` might be a more derived type when you instantiate it. The other way around, `ClassOf<T>` can't be assigned to `this._type` because it's missing the static method.

You could perform an assertion to `any` and then to `ClassOf<T>` but I don't necessarily recommend that.

What about moving `typeof Model` to your type parameter?

``` ts
class RefArray<TModel extends typeof Model> extends Array<ObjectID> {
    private _type: TModel;
    public get type(): TModel { return this._type; };

    public resolve(): Array<TModel> {
        let ModelClass = <TModel>this._type;
        return this.map((cData: Object): TModel => {
            return <TModel>ModelClass.fromData(cData);
        });
    }

    constructor(aClass: TModel) {
        super();
        this._type = aClass;
    }
}
```

