When you use `var export_mongoose = _mongoose`, `export_mongoose` only takes on the _value side_ of `_mongoose`.

Instead of using `export_mongoose`, I suggest you instead export the import directly:

``` TypeScript
declare module "test" {
    export import _mongoose = require("mongoose");
}
```

Try 

``` Typescript
declare module "test" {
    import mongoose = require("mongoose");
    export import export_mongoose = mongoose;
```

The `import...=` declaration above creates an alias to all meanings of `mongoose`.

I would use the ES6 import/export syntax here.

``` Typescript
declare module "test" {
   // import it locally 
   import * as mongoose from "mongoose";
   // use the import
   var test_var: mongoose.Model<...>;

   // export it directly from "mongoose" module
   export * from "mongoose";
```

Yes - if you're still intent on doing it the way you wanted, you can do something like

``` TypeScript
declare module "test" {
    import * as mongoose from "mongoose";
    export { mongoose as export_mongoose };
}
```

