While attempting to create a decorator for checking if a parameter is `null` and throwing, I found that the code emitted is overwriting the wrapper function I'm installing.

``` ts
function throwIfNull(target: any, key: string, index: number) {
    let original = target[key];
    return function () {
        if (arguments[index] === null) {
            throw new TypeError(`Argument #${index} must be defined and not null`);
        }
        original.apply(this, arguments);
    };
}

class Foo {
    bar(@throwIfNull baz?: any) {
        console.log('here');
    }
}

var foo = new Foo();
foo.bar(null);
```

The emitted JavaScript (ES5) is:

``` js
var __decorate = this.__decorate || function (decorators, target, key, desc) {
    if (typeof Reflect === "object" && typeof Reflect.decorate === "function") return Reflect.decorate(decorators, target, key, desc);
    switch (arguments.length) {
        case 2: return decorators.reduceRight(function(o, d) { return (d && d(o)) || o; }, target);
        case 3: return decorators.reduceRight(function(o, d) { return (d && d(target, key)), void 0; }, void 0);
        case 4: return decorators.reduceRight(function(o, d) { return (d && d(target, key, o)) || o; }, desc);
    }
};
var __param = this.__param || function(index, decorator) { return function (target, key) { decorator(target, key, index); } };
function throwIfNull(target, key, index) {
    var original = target[key];
    return function () {
        if (arguments[index] === null) {
            throw new TypeError("Argument #" + index + " must be defined and not null");
        }
        original.apply(this, arguments);
    };
}
var Foo = (function () {
    function Foo() {
    }
    Foo.prototype.bar = function (baz) {
        console.log('here');
    };
    Object.defineProperty(Foo.prototype, "bar",
        __decorate([
            __param(0, throwIfNull)
        ], Foo.prototype, "bar", Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(Foo.prototype, "bar")));
    return Foo;
})();
var foo = new Foo();
foo.bar(null);
```

The problem stems from `__decorate` returning the original property descriptor because the function returned by `__param` doesn't return anything. This causes the original property descriptor to be installed back onto `Foo.prototype`.

comments.body:
If function created by __param is modified to return the value returned by decorate(), then that value will have to be a property descriptor; not just a function.  @bryanforbes' decorator above would have to change to something like this:

``` javascript
function throwIfNull(target: any, key: string, index: number) {
    let original = target[key];
    var property = Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(proto, key);
    property.value = function () {
        if (arguments[index] === null) {
            throw new TypeError(`Argument #${index} must be defined and not null`);
        }
        original.apply(this, arguments);
    };
    return property;
}
```

I am wondering if that is the intent of parameter decorators?

Parameter decorators are not able to change the target. If you want to be able to change the target, you have to use a method decorator instead.

``` ts
class Foo {
  @validate
  bar(@throwIfNull baz) {}
}
```

Here, throwIfNull would be a marker that writes some kind of metadata, and validate would wrap the method.

Here are the four decorator types:

``` ts
type ClassDecorator = <TFunction extends Function>(target: TFunction) => TFunction | void;
type PropertyDecorator = (target: Object, propertyKey: string | symbol) => void;
type MethodDecorator = <T>(target: Object, propertyKey: string | symbol, descriptor: TypedPropertyDescriptor<T>) => TypedPropertyDescriptor<T> | void;
type ParameterDecorator = (target: Object, propertyKey: string | symbol, parameterIndex: number) => void;
```

Class decorators, and method decorators are the ones that can return a value, and hence change the behavior. the property and parameter ones do not get to return anything.

