I _believe_ (and others on the team should feel free to correct me) that this has to do with the way in which contextual typing takes effect (i.e. it _doesn't_ take effect on the return type of a call¬†expression).

In other words, `lengths`'s return type doesn't impact your call's type, and so the language computes the type `(string | number)[]`.

You can get the behavior you want by giving your lambda a return type.

``` TypeScript
function lengths(xs: string[]): [string, number][] {
    return xs.map((x): [string, number] => [x, x.length]);
}
```

