Not quite sure what you mean by "trying to define variable of Blob". Do you mean define a value that can be assigned to Blob? The Blob variable represents a constructor function (i.e. it is a variable of a constructor function type). To produce an assignment compatible value, you'll likely want to declare a class. For example:

``` typescript
class MyBlob implements Blob {
    type: string;
    size: number;
    constructor(blobParts?: any[], options?: BlobPropertyBag) {
    }
    msDetachStream(): any {
        return undefined;
    }
    slice(start?: number, end?: number, contentType?: string): Blob {
        return undefined;
    }
    msClose(): void {
    }
}
```

You can then assign the class constructor function to the `Blob` variable:

``` typescript
Blob = MyBlob;
```

Note, it is important to understand that there are two distinct and different things called Blob: A type (produced by the interface declaration) and a variable (with an _unnamed_ constructor function type whose return value is the Blob interface). In type positions, Blob refers to the interface type, and in value positions (such as expressions) Blob refers to the constructor function.

