It is possible to "implement" a class -- but it means treating the class as an interface, so you'll have to create an implementation of every one of its members.
However, if the class you're implementing has a private member, it's impossible to implement.
```ts
class A {
	private x: number;
}
// Error: Types have separate declarations of a private property 'x'.
class B implements A {
	private x: number;
}
```

It's correct that we give you this error message, because if `B implements A`, you would expect to be able to assign a `B` to an `A`, but you can't assign anything to a class with a private member unless it's derived from that class via `extends`. So the error message should just tell you that instead of telling you to implement a property that you can't possibly implement.

In your case, if you really don't intend to use `extends`, you must define an interface and have both classes implement that.

