comments.body:
`Promise.reject` never changes the contextual type of Promise. So I think the fix your thoughts would be this. However, it is buggy. Anyone cannot trust a `reason` parameter type. Do you really need that?

``` diff
interface PromiseConstructor {
-    reject(reason: any): Promise<never>;
-    reject<T>(reason: any): Promise<T>;
+    reject(reason?: any): Promise<never>;
+    reject<T>(reason: T): Promise<never>;
}
```

Add:

Could you accept the following fix?

``` diff
interface PromiseConstructor {
-    new <T>(executor: (resolve: (value?: T | PromiseLike<T>) => void, reject: (reason?: any) => void) => void): Promise<T>;
+    new <T>(executor: (resolve: (value: T | PromiseLike<T>) => void, reject: (reason?: any) => void) => void): Promise<T>;
}
```

for the current strict typings of `Promise.resolve`.

``` ts
    resolve<T>(value: T | PromiseLike<T>): Promise<T>;
    resolve(): Promise<void>;
```

The cast is useful if you had something like this:

``` typescript
function looksLikeAsync(): Promise<string> {
    if (someCondition) {
        return Promise.resolve('foo');
    }
    else {
        return Promise.reject<string>(new Error('I hate kittens'));
    }
}

looksLikeAsync()
    .then((str) => { /* do something */ }, (err) => { /* handle error */ });
```

Previously though `Promise<void>` was not assignable to `Promise<string>` but `Promise<never>` is always assignable to `Promise<string>`, though I suspect changing the typing and taking away the generic would break other peoples code who previously had to cast before `never` was a thing.

For example, the following case returns the unexpected type. This is very bad.

``` ts
// An expected return type is Promise<void>, actually it returns Promise<string | void>
function f() {
  return Promise.resolve()
    .then(() => Promise.resolve(), () => Promise.reject<string>(''));
}
```

sorry, meant `Promise<string>`. so:

``` ts
function f() {
    return Promise.resolve()
        .then(() => Promise.resolve(), () => <Promise<string>>Promise.reject(''));
}
```

is basically the same as:

``` ts
// An expected return type is Promise<void>, actually it returns Promise<string | void>
function f() {
  return Promise.resolve()
    .then(() => Promise.resolve(), () => Promise.reject<string>(''));
}
```

except that the later is easier to write and nicer to read.

